      <div class="security-grid">
        <div class="security-card">
          <span class="security-icon">📐</span>
          <h3>Stack Vertically</h3>
          <p>Fort Knox containers are 8.5 feet tall. Use the full height — put heavy items on the bottom, lighter boxes on top. You'll be amazed how much fits when you stack efficiently.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="security-card">
          <span class="security-icon">🪑</span>
          <h3>Disassemble Furniture</h3>
          <p>Remove table legs, bed frames, and shelving units before loading. Flat-packed furniture uses a fraction of the space. Keep hardware in labeled bags taped to each piece.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="security-card">
          <span class="security-icon">📦</span>
          <h3>Use Uniform Boxes</h3>
          <p>Same-size boxes stack neatly with no wasted gaps. Medium boxes (18" × 18" × 16") are the best all-purpose size — large enough for most items, small enough to stack safely.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="security-card">
          <span class="security-icon">🚪</span>
          <h3>Create an Aisle</h3>
          <p>Leave a narrow path down the center so you can reach items at the back without unloading everything. This is especially important if you'll be accessing the unit during a long-term rental.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="security-card">
          <span class="security-icon">🛋️</span>
          <h3>Fill Empty Spaces</h3>
          <p>Stuff drawers, appliances, and hollow items with soft goods — towels, linens, clothing. Fill the inside of the washer and dryer. Every cubic foot of air is wasted space.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="security-card">
          <span class="security-icon">📋</span>
          <h3>Load Strategically</h3>
          <p>Put items you'll need first near the door. Seasonal items can go to the back. Heavy furniture and appliances along the walls, boxes in the center. Think about unloading day while you load.</p>
        </div>
